                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 816.00/145.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Minister to Salvador</gloss>
                        to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">San Salvador</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-01-10T14:00:00-05:56">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 10, 1912—2 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The President of Salvador has requested me to telegraph the Department that in
                    consequence of Estrada Cabrera’s increased military activities along the
                    frontier the situation is becoming graver every day and that an invasion of
                    Salvador from Guatemala and an outbreak of hostilities may be looked for at any
                    time. The Minister for Foreign Affairs has just informed me that the Government
                    of Salvador is in receipt of telegrams saying that every person desiring to
                    cross into Guatemala from Salvador is turned back by order of the President of
                    Guatemala; that Baron von Merck, accompanied by an aide-de-camp, who are
                    officers on the staff of the President of Guatemala, have just crossed the
                    frontier en route to this city bearing an important communication from Estrada
                    Cabrera to President Araujo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Heimke</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
